text: This is a series - if you missed part 1 and 2, go back to my page and check them out as they are all important parts of the puzzle!  I got a lot of questions yesterday about if my parents die. This plan of moving to live with my parents is very practical right now as my parents are just now turning 50, in great health, and very stable. However, in 15-20 years, likely changes will be made to this plan. One of the things we could do is up my husband's life insurance policy to provide for more income. If my parents were to die while I was living with them, they would leave my brother and I their inheritance. I want to make it clear THIS IS NOT ADVICE. This is simply me sharing what WE have done. Every situation is a little different. Also, I am not the most qualified to share advice about this by any means. My hope is that this is a good starting point if any of you are new to all this!  I think a lot of people look at a woman who got married at 18 and think oh, there is no way she could live life on her own if something happened. Really? I thought women could do anything ü§îüòé In all seriousness, my husband and I have worked through a lot of what ifs together and I think that's really important. Not to live life in fear but to be reasonably prepared. Because unless we get raptured, my husband WILL die. So will I. So best be prepared because we know our days are numbered.  #tradwives #tradwife #traditionalwife

text: The long and short of it: I'm autistic. Okay so I don't know that for sure, maybe one day I will get diagnosed, but sensory issues are the cause of this being my safe hairstyle.  - it keeps my hair out of my face but doesn't pull or give me a headache - it's protective to sleep in  - it stays really well so I only braid my hair every 2 days - it gives me soft waves - it looks cute with a bandana over it  - it takes me less than 5 minutes and no mirror to do When there are this many benefits, why would I do something else ü§£ but also I am overstimulated SO easily by hairstyles, I haven't found another good low stimulation one. If you have, let me know and I'll try it! But even like, one braid in the back bothers me. ü´† I find a lot of people criticize my braids as being infantalizing, but I find that interesting because the concept of hairstyles having an age limit is very old-fashioned. And one that I, as a generally old-fashioned person, do not ascribe to! Girls would no longer wear their hair down once they reached a certain age. I don't believe that age should have a limit on my hair. My mom is nearly 50 and has pink hair, so at 23, there should be no problem for me to wear braids.  Anyway, hope you enjoyed that little monologue!  #traditional #tradwife

text: Growing up, we always called this shepherd's pie, but actually¬†that's made with sheep, so this is cottage pie! It's such an easy comfort food and great for those hearty eaters like my husband who works in the wind and sun every day. Here is the recipe!¬† Muttie's Cottage Pie Makes a 9x13 casserole dish (can be easily halved)¬† 2lbs ground beef 1 onion, minced 1 garlic clove 1 tsp salt 1/2 tsp pepper 1/4 cup & 2 tbsp¬†Worcestershire sauce 1 bag frozen veggies 3/4 cup flour 1 quart of beef broth Mashed potatoes¬† Brown meat and onion together over medium heat. Stir in flour, then broth. Cook until thickened¬†and bubbly. Add seasonings and veggies. Put in the casserole dish, then top with mashed¬†potatoes! Bake at 350 until bubbly and slightly browned on top. Enjoy!¬† For mashed potatoes, no one in my family has a recipe, but we just eyeball it! Boiled potatoes, mashed with lots of butter and salt, then we add sour cream, cream, and cream cheese. You can omit either sour cream or cream cheese but adding both makes them SO decadent.¬† Enjoy!! #traditional #traditionalwife #tradwives

text: Probably gonna make a lot of people mad with this one üòÖ One of the things I have sworn to never do on here is promote a network marketing company. Now listen, if you are a part of one, I still like you!! So so many of you are and I still love you all üòÖü•∞ü§£ Network marketing is just not my thing. For many many reasons which I'll list a few here: 1) The majority of people who sign up with one do not make money but actually tend to lose money.  2) The target audience for MLM sign-ups are people who need an additional income. I see this as very predatory especially because these women tend to be in a tight space financially, then they have to invest in starting with this company and see point 1 - often lose money in the process üò≠ 3) It's more about recruiting more people than it is about selling a quality product. To me that just feels icky.  4) The people who succeed are often working very hard, very long hours and that often cuts into their time with their family. Basically it can circle back on you and put you in a position you didn't want to be in, in the first place.  5) People who do network marketing often (not always) tend to be very defensive about what they do. I have seen reels on here where someone voices their opiniom about how they don't like MLMs and the comments section is always very defensive. To me that doesn't make sense because why do you need to defend it so hard, your company is huge it can handle it üò≠ Listen, if you are in network marketing and you are happy I am happy for you! Seriously. This post is just to say that if you've been considering joining an MLM, do your research and consider how much time you'll have to put into it. As someone who is an entrepreneur and has owned her own business (like an actual business, not recruiting folks in a downline) I know firsthand what it's like to work your butt off and personally I'd rather do that for my own company, that I own 100% of and control everything involved in it. Just my personal preference.  Stay savvy out there.  #traditionalroles #tradwife #mlm #networkmarketing

text: When I said we are not "equal partners", I did not mean that we are not equal in value. We ARE equal in value. Both of us are incredibly important to the household and both of is are made in God's image and equally loved by Him.  I simply meant that the way our marriage is run is not an equal partnership, where both work, both split everything 50/50, etc. We are not interchangeable partners. We are a team with separate roles.  Now if you're going to say "We were concerned for you because you said your husband is the head of the household", I've heard that. That is his role, and that does not make me any less as a person. Essentially in the business of the home he is my boss. A good boss, a good leader, always asks and considers the opinions of those he is leading. If he has no regard for the opinions of others, he is not a leader, he is a dictator.  I found it amusing that there were people who were absolutely convinced that both my husband and I should be the head of the household. That does not work. Have you heard of the snakes with two heads? They never last long. We are a team, and he is the team lead, because a team needs direction otherwise it can go two separate ways and that is incredibly ineffective. Have you ever worked on a group project where there was no one who took the lead? I've heard those don't work very effectively.  Anyway, just know that this is my decision, I knew that this family structure was what I wanted before I got married. I wasn't hoodwinked into anything and so far it's worked great. He can do what he does best and I can do what I do best and neither of us are stressed. In fact we've had very few marital struggles. Probably because we both focus on serving each other and following the Lord's design.  Oh and if your marriage isn't like this, I'm not threatening you so don't feel threatened. That's your decision, not mine.  #traditionalwife #traditionalroles

text: You would be surprised at the amount of times I've been told that I'm not a tradwife because I don't have children. Or because I make money. Or because I have a fridge (seriously!!). Which is ridiculous in my opinion because 1) infertility as always been around, just less common, 2) women have always made money, especially from home, and 3) it's normal to use the technology of the time, whether we have traditional values and skills or not.  The funny thing is that the people who are pushing these requirements on me, are not other tradwives. Actually, the people who have the narrowest ideas of what it means to be a traditional wife, are the people who are against the lifestyle.  As a Christian tradwife, the main thing I see that makes me a traditional wife are my traditional values. That God is first in our lives. That my husband is the head of the family. Children are a blessing. That men and women are completely different, and have different roles in the family.  It's not about me not making an income, or wearing dresses, or having tons of children. It's about the order of the household and priorities and those things all fall into place... I only work part time because my priority is the home.  I wear dresses because I choose to look feminine and graceful and for me, dresses accomplish that goal well.  I want to have as many children as God will give us, because I believe children are a blessing from the Lord.  Being a tradwife is more about the core beliefs and values you hold than it is about every particular thing you do. And I would venture to say that's how we all make our decisions.  Thoughts? I'd love to chat more in the comments! #tradwife #traditionalwife #tradwives

text: You're not equal partners?? No! We aren't. We are two people, who have equal value but incredibly different roles, gifting, and purposes in the household. Our marriage is not a 50/50 split. No, we have patterned our marriage after what we see in scripture.  Andrew is the head of the household. He is the leader of the family, the one God ordained to provide for and protect us, physically and spiritually. I do not go to him for every little decision, but instead he has designated parts of the household where I have dominion over. When it comes to decisions, we make them together but he weighs the options and has the final say. We are a team, and he leads the team.  I on the other hand, get to do what I do best. My domain includes the kitchen, cleaning, purchases for the family, health. While either of us could step in for the other (and do occasionally on a need basis), we aren't very good at it. We have designated roles in the household not only because we see that in scripture but also because it just works. Andrew takes care of the things I hate doing, and vice versa.  But above all I think the most controversial thing about out marriage is not the structure but the fact that we put each other first. As Christians we are called to imitate Christ and Jesus literally died for us. We die to ourselves every day, putting aside selfish thoughts and serving the other instead. Marriage like this takes sacrifice, but we are willing to be radical. P.S. As you can see here I am talking about MY marriage, not anyone else's. If your marriage is structured completely differently that's fine! We have to make our own decisions for our lives and I will not be held accountable for yours, but for mine. ü•∞ #trad #traditional #traditionalwife

text: "So then you're just a normal woman" Nope, I'm still traditional. What the majority of us tradwives mean when we say we are traditional, is that we follow traditional gender roles in our marriage.  My husband is the head of the household, leader, main provider.  I as his wife am his helpmeet. I submit to him and take care of the home (and future children üôè). My role can include working. As a helpmeet, I do what helps him. Right now, taking care of the house and running my side hustles is helpful (and enjoyable for me!) Modern marriages often operate on a 50/50 egalitarian mindset, that both husband and wife are interchangeable in the relationship. Whereas my husband and I know that God created us very differently, with unique strengths and skills to fill our roles. We thrive off of this and work together well. Neither of us can fill in for the other completely. That's what makes us traditional. Women have always worked. The Proverbs 31 woman like I mentioned sold fine linen and bought land. But in the Bible women were extolled for being good homemakers and I see that as my primary responsibility. When children come along I would happily give up my job to raise them, and because of my husband, I can.  Some tradwives bring in an income, some don't. We are not all identical or believe exactly the same things, but we are striving towards a main goal. ü•∞ #trad #tradwife #traditional #traditionalwife

text: Someone asked me the other day why my husband and I have gender roles in our marriage. It's two-fold for us.  First off I believe God created man and woman with two different purposes and equipped them with different strengths and abilities. We are both equal in value but unique; I do not believe we are just interchangeable humans.  In the Bible, I see women being homemakers as the norm. In Titus the older women are called to encourage the younger women to be keepers at home, and the Proverbs 31 woman was also extolled for taking good care of her home. We are called to be our husband's helpers - and while that often looks like taking care of the home it can also look like bringing in extra income. We are also called to bear children, a unique ability that only women have.  Men, on the other hand are the head of the family. They are called to love, care for and serve their family as Christ serves the church. In modern day this often looks like the man being the main provider. In other times in history it meant the man went out and hunted for food for his family, or protected them from marauders. Provision and protection are two main roles of the husband. (Spiritual Leadership is another.) But the second side of this, that confirms our roles to us, is that we genuinely thrive when doing what we believe God made us for. I worked for 6 years, and that was an extremely stressful time. When I finally was able to come home and tend to my household, I felt so much freedom and my health got so much better. I see nothing wrong with working - but when it comes before my home, everything struggles. I feel so much peace when my home is in order.  My husband on the other hand THRIVES on work. Especially long, hard, physical labor. What would literally drive my health into the ground and cause me to be stressed and frustrated, he loves! In fact we have an inside joke that he hates vacations because he's not working ü§£ It's remarkable, but we really do believe men are made for work! Of course these are just my thoughts. We can absolutely disagree! How we live our life is our problem, and how you live yours is yours. But hopefully this answers some questions ü•∞

text: All of these outfits are modest.  Some of you will agree and think that I'm still dressing very conservatively (which I am). Others will disagree, that's fine.  You see, I am personally convicted that everything I'm wearing in this video is modest. I have a clean and right heart before the Lord. And one day, I will face God and give an account for all my actions.  However, you may be convicted differently. Maybe you believe wearing pants is wrong because of that verse in Deuteronomy that warns against wearing mens' clothes. (Not getting into that debate here or today, FYI.)  That's fine too. Because you also will give an account for YOUR actions. But just yours. Not mine.  God loves it when people seek to follow Him. You know what He doesn't love? People who invent rules to feel more spiritual or people who impose their personal convictions on others. Remember in the Gospels when Jesus chastised the Pharisees for imposing so many unhelpful, man-made rules about the Sabbath? He said that the Sabbath was made for man, not man for the Sabbath - i.e. it's supposed to help us! To give us a rest and remind us of the rest we have in Christ.  I see modesty similarly. It's for our protection, dignity, and witness to others. But the choices you make about what you wear must be between you and God. Don't take that flippantly. You are welcome to share why you are particularly convicted, but know that it's not your clothes that save you or anyone else. It's the work Christ did on the cross, and seeking to honor Him with our bodies is a result of a joyful heart, not a heart seeking rules. What are your thoughts?  #tradwife #modesty #christianmodesty #christiangirl

text: A slightly more realistic one for this trend üòâ In stories we've been talking about all the videos we've been seeing recently where people are claiming they've made thousands, even hundreds of thousands from posting a simple video of them driving or drinking coffee. While that sounds wonderful, that isn't the story of most of us content creators on here.  In reality, most of us content creators who are making money are posting higher quality content that takes longer to make, trying to create valuable digital products, and in general bring value to people's lives. I think of @reallyverycrunchy for example - her social media is her livelihood, but look at the work she puts into her videos!  Anyway, as someone who has been creating content on IG for about 5 years, and who started actively putting work and time into this account one year ago, I thought this "what I made" video would be helpful for you.  If you've been wondering how to make money on instagram - I don't have a course or guide to sell you. IG does not monetize! I've only been able to bring in money via my Patreon (where I am also constantly creating valuable content), and affiliates (I made $400 this year from affiliates). So, if you want to make money online, maybe work on building up a following and then create digital products that hit your audience's pain points.  It's all about value. ‚ù§ #tradwife #traditionalwife #contentcreator

text: "Tradwife" is a fairly inclusive, yet exclusive term. We all look different - some of us wear prairie style clothes, some 1950s, others just modern clothes.  Some of us have children, others don't.  Some of us homestead and live in the country, and others live in the city.  Some of us rely 100% on our husband's income, some of us work!  None of these things define us as traditional wives, and really, all of that is traditional. Even working - women have been working for all of time!  I think the main thing is that as traditional wives, we seek to follow God's design for the family. We respect our husbands as the main breadwinner and the head of the home. As wives, we see our roles as the help meet - and what we do as helper to our husbands will vary from family to family. Our homes are our priority - and our families even more so. Tending to the home is primarily our role as wives, so, we prioritize that over our hobbies or jobs.  And lastly, we believe God designed men and women with completely separate sets of abilities, talents, and roles. We are not interchangeable but complimentary to one another. This often drives much of our lifestyles.  P.S. I understand that, while much of this post is true, I may not be speaking for every woman who calls herself a traditional wife. This is mainly what I believe and have observed from others in the community, but I understand that there are caveats and varying opinions. My word is not the gospel truth, so please don't think that I believe it is. ‚ù§Ô∏è #tradwife #traditionalwife #homemaker
